Nasal asssimilation analysis - English monolingual

Opening and files and subsetting them.

eval_data = read.csv(paste0(results_folder, "nasal_eval.csv"))



#changing numbers to more meaningful names
eval_data["v_or_c"][eval_data["v_or_c"] == 0] <- "cons."
eval_data["v_or_c"][eval_data["v_or_c"] == 5] <- "vowel"

eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 1] <- "m"
eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 2] <- "n"
eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 3] <- ""
eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 4] <- ""

eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 6] <- "a"
eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 7] <- "i"
eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 8] <- "e"
eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 9] <- "o"
eval_data["nasal"][eval_data["nasal"] == 10] <- ""

eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 11] <- ""
eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 12] <- ""
eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 13] <- ""
eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 14] <- ""
eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 15] <- ""

eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 16] <- "labial"
eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 17] <- "coronal"
eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 18] <- "palatal"
eval_data["following"][eval_data["following"] == 19] <- "velar"

eval_data= eval_data[- grep(20, eval_data$nasal),] #deleteing velar nasals bc I could not deal with them 


eval_data$following <- as.factor(eval_data$following)  # Convert character column to factor
eval_data$nasal <- as.factor(eval_data$nasal)  # Convert character column to factor

Descriptive stats.

cons  %>%
  group_by(nasal, following) %>%
  get_summary_stats(loss_mean, type = "mean_sd")

  group_by(nasal, following) %>%
  get_summary_stats(loss_mean, type = "mean_sd")

Another way of showing descriptive stats. n The number of observations for each treatment. mean The mean value for each treatment. sd The standard deviation of each treatment. stderr The standard error of each treatment. That is the standard deviation / sqrt (n). LCL, UCL The upper and lower confidence intervals of the mean. That is to say, you can be 95% certain that the true mean falls between the lower and upper values specified for each treatment group assuming a normal distribution. median The median value for each treatment. min, max The minimum and maximum value for each treatment. IQR The inner quartile range of each treatment. That is the 75th percentile 25th percentile. LCLmed, UCLmed The 95% confidence interval for the median.

cons %>% select(nasal, following, loss_mean) %>% group_by(nasal, following) %>% 
  summarise(n=n(), 
            mean=mean(loss_mean, na.rm = FALSE), 
            sd=sd(loss_mean, na.rm = FALSE),
            stderr=sd/sqrt(n),
            LCL = mean - qt(1 - (0.05 / 2), n - 1) * stderr,
            UCL = mean + qt(1 - (0.05 / 2), n - 1) * stderr,
            median=median(loss_mean, na.rm = FALSE),
            min=min(loss_mean, na.rm = FALSE), 
            max=max(loss_mean, na.rm = FALSE),
            IQR=IQR(loss_mean, na.rm = FALSE),
            LCLmed = MedianCI(loss_mean, na.rm=FALSE)[2],
            UCLmed = MedianCI(loss_mean, na.rm=FALSE)[3])
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'nasal'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Inferential stats.

model1 <- lm(log(-1*loss_mean) ~ nasal*following, data = cons)
model2 <- lm(log(-1*loss_mean)  ~ nasal+following, data = cons)


model.set <- list(model1, model2)
model.names <- c("int", "2way")

aictab(model.set, model.names)
autoplot(model1)
